Pulsus Paradoxus

[!INFO] pulsus paradoxus
A fall of Systolic BP by ≥ 10 mmHg during inspiration.

A form of Type 1 Diabetes that has slower onset and is diagnosed in adults.
Often misdiagnosed for T2DM but doesn't respond to T2DM treatment because the pathology is deficient insulin production, not insulin resistance.

See also [[2020-NOV-BasicSciences#Monogenic diabetes mellitus]]

Management of Diabetes insipidus:

  • Central -> Desmopressin
  • Nephrogenic -> Thiazides!, low salt / protein diet.


Lithium has a very narrow therapeutic window and several things can raise lithium concentrations leading to toxicity.
- Fine tremor, polyuria, polydypsia, metallic taste, goiter, hypothyroidism, weight gain, oedema, diabetes insipidus (nephrogenic) and arrhythmias
- NOTE: polyuria is a feature of therapeutic range lithium levels.
- Management of acute toxicity: improve renal elimination or dialysis (but dialysis only removes the plasma content. Cellular content is slow to shift to the plasma)
- Drugs interfering with renal excretion of lithium: Thiazides >> loop diuretics, ACEi, ARB, NSAIDS,
- Lithium can cause hyper and hypothyroisism; but mainly hypo.

Leukemoid reaction refers to a white blood cell (WBC) count >50,000/microL from causes other than leukemia.

  • (Usually caused by severe reaction to an infection).
  • Other causes:
    • Severe Haemolysis
    • Massive haemorrhage
    • Metastatic cancer with bone deposists.

It's a common clinical problem to differentiate leukemoid reaction from chronic myeloid leukemia.
Other features of leukemoid reaction

  • High leukocyte alkaline phosphatase score. (In CML, the alkaline phosphatase score is LOW)
  • Toxic granulation "Dohle bodies" seen in neutrophils.
  • Left shift of neutrophils. (but most cells will still be mature neutrophils; in CML, the proportion of immature cells is higher)

Monogenic diabetes mellitus (MODY)

[!TIP] Mnemonic:
LADA -> Type 1 diabetes presenting in adults.
MODY -> Young patient (so looks like T1DM) but has strong family history -> MODY

  • Classic type 1 DM does not develop in infants younger than 6 months of age. Monogenic diabetes is likely if DM occurs at this age. -> ie. the glucokinase mutation variant.

Body habitus is lean, unlike type 2 DM and there are no features of insulin resistance.

GORD - gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (gastrooesophageal)

#2016GM-OCT/Q11

Physiology
Normally, the LOS remains closed between swallows because of intrinsic properties of it's muscles.
Transient lower oesophageal sphincter relaxations occur during swallowing (TLESRs) to allow food to pass.
The frequency of TLESRs increases in patients with GORD allowing gastric contents to reflux.
Other anti reflux mechanisms:

  • Flap valve of intraabdominal oesophagus
  • Mucosal rosette
  • Diaphgramatic crura - pinchcock

Any residual reflux is cleared by secondary peristalsis, salivary bicarbonate, and gravity.

An "Acid pocket" of acid not neutralized by incoming food and fluid and serve as a reservoir of 'refluxable' acid. This can be targeted with an antacid-alginate combination.

No correlation between heartburn and presence of oesophagitis.

[!WARNING] Severe oesophagitis can cause haematemesis or iron deficiency anaemia from blood loss.

Symptoms

  • Heart burn
  • Water brash (Excess salivation caused by acid reflux into the mouth)
  • Cough and asthma!

Risk factors

  • Obesity, pregnancy
  • Fat, chocolate, alcohol, coffee
  • Antimuscarinics and CCBs
  • Systemic sclerosis
  • Treatment of achalasia cardia
  • hiatus hernia

Diagnosis
Treatment is initiated on clinical diagnosis.

However, Endcoscopy is indicated in

  • refractory cases or
  • those with red flag symptoms (dysphagia, weight loss, bleeding) or
  • for patients with longstanding reflux (≥10 years) as they have a high risk of [[2020-NOV-BasicSciences#Barrett oesophagus|Barrett's Oesophagus]]
    Demonstration of oesophagitis or Barrett's oesophagus on endoscopy confirms GORD.

Endoscopy is sensitive for oesophagitis but it will miss nonerosive reflux disease. (NERD)

  • NERD doesn't respond to PPIs.
  • Most patients with NERD are female
  • Symptoms are 'often' functional or due to hypersensitive oesophagus.

The most sensitive test -> 24 ambulatory pH monitoring.

The DeMeester score is a composite of pH and manometry (?and other) and if ≥ 14.72, indicates presence of reflux.

Treatment

  1. Alginate containing antacids - 10ml tds - most common treatment. Forms a gel raft which prevents reflux.
  2. PPIs - 4 weeks course of once daily PPI resolves symptoms in 60%.
  3. H2 receptor blockers.
  4. Prokinetics
  5. invasive
    1. Endoscopic endoluminal gastropilication
    2. Surgical : Nissen fundoplication for hiatus hernia, Linx reflux management system.

Sjogren syndrome

Keratoconjuntivis sicca - term for the occular manifestations of Sjogrens.

  • Characterized by sudden onset dry mouth leading to difficulty in swallowing.
  • Hard painless swellings of the salivary glands.
  • Symptoms are very similar to Sjogren's syndrome.
  • Sjogren's disease is one possible cause of this.

🔖CRP

  • CRP - is an [[2023-SEMPaper#Acute phase reactants|Acute phase reactants]].

  • Is a Protein pentamer produced in the liver.

  • CRP was the first Pattern recognition receptor (PRR) to be identified.

  • Has proinflammatory and anti-inflammatory properties. Anti > pro.

  • Synthesis is increased by IL-6 produced by macrophages in response to inflammation.

  • Increases within 2 hours of an insult. Half life of 18 hours.

  • Roles: Identifies and binds to foreign molecules and damaged local cells. Activates the classical [[#Complement system|complement]] pathway AND binds Fc receptors to facillitate phagocytosis - opsonin

  • cardiovascular disease - elevated baseline CRP has been associated with incr. risk of ASCVD but compared to other risk factors, the added risk is low.

  • Also synthesized by endothelium in small amounts - ?source

  • CRP can be normal in SLE due to the production of interferons which inhibit hepatic CRP production.

ESR

  • ESR has a longer half life than CRP. Therefore, ESR is used for chronic conditions. CRP is used for acute conditions.
  • ESR is increased in inflammation because elevated fibrinogen (and other proteins) levels decrease the repelling effect of negative charges on RBCs and promote rouleaux formation.

There are only two circumstances where the erythrocyte sedimentation rate is superior

  • detecting low-grade bone and joint infections,
  • and monitoring disease activity in systemic lupus erythematosus. Source

    • Focal onset aware seizures: aka simple partial seizures; person remains awake and aware during the seizure.
    • Focal onset impaired awareness seizures: aka complex partial seizures.

Advanced life support

Key points

Source

[!INFO] Signs of ROSC

  • purposeful movement
  • Sharp rise in ETCO2.
  • waking up
  • presence of arterial waveform.

Ventilation

  • Rate: 30 : 2 compressions to breaths.
  • Start with basic airway techniques and progress according to skill of resuscitator
  • Breaths are given over 1 second to achieve good chest expansion.
  • Compressions are interuppted only for 5 seconds to allow airway placement.
  • Continous breaths are given if "advanced airway" present:
    • = ET tube or Supra glottic Airway. Breaths given at rate of 10 breaths / min.
    • 30:2 can be used even if airway is in place if compression results in gas leaks.
  • Capnography is used to confirm tube position.

Cardiac

  • Amiodarone is given after 3 shocks (i.e of patients with VF or pulseless VT)

Medication

  • Intraosseous access is acceptable if intravenous access is not achievable.
  • Adrenaline
    • Non shockable rhythm: Adrenaline 1mg ASAP.
    • Shockable rhythm: Adrenaline 1mg IV AFTER THE 3RD SHOCK
    • Adrenaline is repeated every 3 to 5 minutes. (no mention of alternate cycles in the guidelines)
  • Amiodarone
    • First dose of 300mg after 3rd shock.
    • Second dose of 150mg after 5th shock.
    • lidocaine 100mg and 50mg can be used to replace the above doses.
    • Thrombolysis : consider if pulmonary emoblism is suspected -> Then CPR should be continued for 60 to 90 minutes.
  • Atrpine
    • Only for life threatening bradycardia
    • Not indicated in PEA or asystole.

Fluids
- Only indicated when arrest is caused by hypovolemia.

Manual defibrillation

  • Continue compressions while charging.
  • Ventilation circuits must remain attached; NPo2 or FM02 should be removed and kept 1m away.
  • Any energy level between 120 and 360 can be used for the initial shock. (then escalated at regular energy intervals)
  • Pause CPR for only 5 seconds while shocking.
  • Immediately begin and continue compressions (if patient shows sings of ROSC, pausing compressions is acceptable).
  • Three stacked shocks:
    • This refers to 3 quick successive shocks without starting CPR inbetween. This is regarded as one single shock with respect to the algorithm.
    • can be used only if
    • Initial ventricular fibrillation/pulseless ventricular tachycardia (VF/pVT) occurs during a witnessed, monitored cardiac arrest with a defibrillator immediately available
    • i.e during cardiac catherization
  • Do not use double sequential defibrillator for refractory VF.

Oxygen:
- Maximum possible FiO2 during resuscitation.
- After ROSC, titrate to maintain sat 94-98% to avoid injury by hyperoxia.

POCUS

  • Can be useful; should not cause any delays in the algorithm.
  • RV dilation during arrest doesn't necessarily mean pulmonary embolism.

Tachcardias

  • For periarrest arrthmia, if patient is conscious, sedation or anaesthesia is required before cardioversion.
  • Shocks are synchronized to the R wave.
  • Energy:
    • AF - maximum defibrillator output. (no stepwise increase)
    • Atrial fluttery or paroxysmal SVT: 70 - 120 J and stepwise increase.
    • Ventricular tachcardia : 120 - 150 J

Bradycardias

  • If bradycardia is accompanied by life threatening adverse signs, give 500mcg bolus. Repeat every 3 to 5 minutes upto maximum of 3mg. (i.e 6 times)
  • Atropine is contraindicated in a patient with a cardiac transplant (can cause high degree AV blocks)
  • Isoprenaline infusion and adrenaline infusion are second line if atropine fails.
  • Bradycardia due to MI : give aminophylline (100 - 200mg slow intravenous infusion)
